US Anti-China Tech War
From New York — — The worst diplomatic policy decision ever made by the Americans (including previous generations) is the "War of Choice" launched in 2003 against Iraq, which claimed to eradicate — — in fact, non-existent — — large-scale weapons of mass destruction.
The necessity to understand the disastrous decision-making behind this catastrophic decision has become unprecedentedly significant, as the same logic is being used to defend similar misguided US policies.
The decision to invade Iraq was made under the flawed logic of then-US Vice President Richard Cheney, who claimed that even if large-scale weapons of mass destruction fell into the hands of terrorists, the risk was small (such as 1%) and we should take action based on the assumption that this would happen.
This line of reasoning almost always leads to incorrect decisions.
However, the US and some of its allies are now using Cheneyism to attack Chinese technology.
According to the US government, since we cannot be sure that Chinese technology is safe, we should approach and ban it as if it is definitely harmful.
Correct decision-making will apply probability estimates to alternative measures.
Previous generations, US policymakers should not only consider the 1% risk of large-scale weapons of mass destruction falling into the hands of terrorists, but also the 99% risk of going to war based on multiple defective premises.
By simply emphasizing that 1% risk, Cheney (and many others) has diverted public attention and ignored the fact that the Iraq war lacks legitimacy and would severely destabilize the Middle East and global politics.
But the problem with Cheneyism is not only that it takes action based on a small risk without considering the extremely high potential cost, but also that politicians will always incite fear for certain unknown purposes.
This is what American leaders are doing again: by pointing out and exaggerating some small risks to spark panic over Chinese tech companies.
The most relevant (but not the only) case is the US government's attack on Huawei, a telecommunications technology company.
The US is gradually shutting down its domestic market for the company and working to strangle its global business.
Like Iraq, the US may ultimately cause a geopolitically disastrous event without cause.
I have worked in developing countries and have been paying attention to Huawei's technological progress, because I believe 5G and other digital technologies can provide tremendous impetus for the elimination of poverty and the achievement of other UN sustainable development goals.
I have also had similar interactions with other telecom companies and have encouraged the industry to take more action towards the sustainable development goals.
I have written a short preface to a report on this topic by Huawei (uncompensated) and have been criticized by China haters, so I asked industry leaders and government officials whether there is any evidence that Huawei has any out-of-line behavior, and I repeatedly got the answer that Huawei's conduct is no different from other trusted industry leaders.
However, the US government still believes that Huawei's 5G devices may harm global security.
US officials claim that Huawei's software or hardware "backdoor" may allow the Chinese government to conduct surveillance globally.
They point out that Chinese laws require Chinese companies to cooperate with the government for national security reasons.
But the fact is that it's right in front of us.
Huawei's 5G devices are low in price, high in quality, currently leading many competitors, and have already started to be promoted.
Its high performance comes from huge investments in research and development over the years, scale economics, and the experience of competing in China's digital market.
Considering the importance of this technology to its sustainable development, it would be foolish for low-income economies around the world to refuse to roll out 5G as soon as possible.
However, despite not being able to provide any evidence of backdoors existing, the US is still lobbying the world to stay away from Huawei.
The US's claims are universal.
As a US Federal Communications Commissioner once said: "Countries with 5G will have relevant innovation and set standards for the rest of the world, and that country is unlikely to be the US at this time."
Other countries - especially the UK - have yet to find any backdoors in Huawei's software or hardware.
Even if backdoors are found in the future, it is almost certain that they can be shut down at that time.
About the Huawei debate, it is also a hot topic in Germany, because the US government threatened to reduce intelligence cooperation unless the authorities block Huawei's 5G technology.
Perhaps under the pressure of the US, the head of the German Federal Intelligence Service recently made a statement similar to Cheneyism: "Infrastructure is not a field that is suitable for a group that cannot be fully trusted to enter."
However, he did not provide any specific evidence of wrongdoing.
By contrast, Chancellor Merkel is secretly fighting to open the market to Huawei.
But it's ironic that US complaints actually partly reflect US surveillance activities at home and abroad — although this is no longer news.
Chinese devices may make it harder for the US government to implement secret surveillance.
However, any government's unauthorized surveillance activities should be stopped.
Independent monitoring conducted by the UN to reduce such activities should be part of the global telecommunications system.
In short, we should choose diplomatic and institutional guarantees, rather than engaging in a technological war.
The threatening impact of the US's demands to ban Huawei is not limited to the early rollout of 5G networks, but also poses a huge risk to the system based on rule of law.
Now, the US is no longer the uncontested leader in global technology, and US President Trump and his advisors do not want to compete based on the rule-based system.
Their goal is to contain China's technological rise.
At the same time, they are trying to cripple the World Trade Organization's dispute resolution mechanism, and this move also reflects their model of global rules.
If the Trump administration can "successfully" divide the world into different technological camps, the risk of conflict will multiply in the future.
After World War II, the US advocated for open trade, not only can it improve global efficiency and expand the US technology market, but also it can reverse the collapse of international trade in the 1930s.
However, the collapse of part of the reason is the protectionist tariffs collected by the US according to the Smoot-Hawley Act of 1930, which exacerbated the Great Depression and ultimately led to the rise of Hitler and the outbreak of World War II.
As it is in other fields, inspiring fear and taking action - - rather than following the evidence - - is the path to destruction in international affairs.
Let us stick to reason, evidence, and rules, which is the safest way to go.
Let us establish independent monitoring agencies to reduce the threat of any country using global networks to monitor other countries or launch cyber warfare.
Then the world can quickly use the break-through digital technology to achieve global well-being.
